[In the summer of 1998 ProMED reported the occurrence of equid cases of
West Nile virus encephalitis in Italy. This report of equid infections
with West Nile virus is not surprising. What is surprising is that it has
taken this long to recognize the illness in horses. West Nile virus cycles
between infected birds and mosquitoes. Birds may resolve their viremias by
producing antibodies or by dying but mosquitoes are persistently infected.
If an infected mosquito takes a blood meal from a vertebrate and that
vertebrate is susceptible to the virus, the vertebrate will become
infected. Other livestock and wild vertebrates should be tested to see
whether they have become hosts of the virus. - Mod.CHC
...........................jw/chc/es
